    "synopsis": "1 Enoch 57 brings the second parable to a climactic close with a vision of cosmic restoration. [A] The chapter describes the gathering of Israel's scattered tribes from the ends of the earth, [C] a theme deeply rooted in prophetic literature (Isa 11:11-12, Jer 31:7-10). [C] Enoch witnesses angels measuring out portions of the earth for the righteous, preparing dwelling places for those who will be resurrected. The imagery combines territorial restoration with eschatological judgment: [C] the earth is purified by fire and water, the oppressors are removed, and the righteous inherit a renewed creation. [B] This is not mere political restoration but cosmic renewal — the reversal of exile at every level (spiritual, physical, cosmic). The chapter emphasizes divine sovereignty over history: what appears as permanent dispersion is temporary diaspora under God's watchful governance. The Second Temple context is crucial: [C] this was written during or shortly after the Maccabean crisis, when faithful Jews faced persecution, hellenization, and the desecration of the temple. The promise of return and vindication spoke directly to communities scattered across the Mediterranean and Mesopotamian worlds, wondering if God had abandoned his covenant.",
    
