    "divine_council_note": "The angels in 1 Enoch 57 function as agents of the divine council executing YHWH's decree of restoration. [B] This aligns with the biblical pattern where angels implement God's judgments and blessings (cf. 2 Sam 24:16, 2 Kings 19:35, Dan 10:13). [C] The 'measuring' activity echoes Ezekiel's temple vision (Ezek 40-48), where an angelic figure measures the renewed sanctuary. In divine council theology, measurement = assignment of jurisdiction. [B] When angels measure portions of the earth 'for the righteous,' they are executing a heavenly land-grant decree, allocating inheritance to the covenant people. This is the reversal of Genesis 10-11, where the nations were scattered and assigned to the b'nei 'elohim (Deut 32:8-9 DSS/LXX). Now the roles reverse: [B] the rebellious nations lose their allotments, and the faithful remnant receives measured, prepared portions. The divine council presides over the cosmic real estate transfer.",
    
    "sections": [
        {
            "heading": "Angels with Measuring Ropes — Preparation for Restoration (57:1-2)",
            "body": "[C] Enoch observes angels receiving 'long ropes' and flying toward the north. When he inquires, he is told: 'They have gone to measure.' [C] The measuring motif is deeply biblical. In Zechariah 2:1-5, an angel with a measuring line prepares to measure Jerusalem, symbolizing God's intention to expand and protect the city. In Ezekiel 40-48, an angelic figure meticulously measures the dimensions of the eschatological temple and the tribal land allotments. [B] Measurement in these contexts signifies ownership, preparation, and divine ordering. To measure is to claim and to allocate.<br><br>[C] The direction — 'toward the north' — is significant. In Israelite geography, <strong>the north</strong> was the direction of threat (Babylon, Assyria) but also the mythic location of the divine mountain (Psalm 48:2, Isa 14:13). [B] The angels measuring the north suggests reclamation of territory previously under enemy or rebellious divine control. [C] In ANE cosmology, the north was associated with the assembly of the gods (cf. Baal's Mount Zaphon in Ugaritic texts). Here, YHWH's angels measure and repossess what was once contested space.<br><br>[B] The ropes themselves may symbolize the cords of inheritance (cf. Psalm 16:6, 'The lines have fallen for me in pleasant places'). In ancient land surveys, ropes were used to measure and mark boundaries. [C] Mesopotamian kudurru stones depict divine symbols overseeing boundary measurements. Enoch's vision applies this: the angels are conducting a cosmic cadastral survey, preparing parcels for the righteous remnant."
        },
        {
            "heading": "Measuring for the Righteous and Holy Ones (57:2-3)",
            "body": "[C] The angel explains that the measurements are 'for the righteous and holy ones' — those who will inherit the renewed earth. This echoes the Levitical land distribution in Joshua 13-21, where the promised land was measured and allocated by lot under divine supervision. [B] But this is not merely territorial restoration; it is eschatological inheritance. The righteous receive not just Canaan but portions of the purified cosmos.<br><br>[A] The concept of the righteous inheriting the land is rooted in Psalm 37:9, 11, 29: 'Those who wait for the LORD shall inherit the land... the meek shall inherit the land and delight themselves in abundant peace... the righteous shall inherit the land and dwell upon it forever.' [B] Jesus quotes this in Matthew 5:5 ('Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth'), universalizing the promise beyond ethnic Israel to all who belong to the covenant community through faith.<br><br>[C] The phrase 'holy ones' (qaddishin in Aramaic, hagioi in Greek) is used in Daniel 7:18, 22, 27 to describe those who receive the kingdom after the judgment of the beasts. [B] In Daniel, the 'holy ones' are either the faithful remnant of Israel or the angelic host allied with them — the ambiguity is likely intentional, as the faithful on earth and the loyal council members in heaven are seen as one unified covenant people. 1 Enoch 57 participates in this tradition: the measured portions are for those who have remained faithful under persecution, aligned with the heavenly council's purposes."
        },
        {
            "heading": "The Gathering of the Dispersed — Reversal of Exile (57:3)",
            "body": "[C] The chapter describes the gathering of the scattered ones 'from the ends of the earth.' This is quintessential restoration language. [A] Isaiah 11:12 promises: 'He will raise a signal for the nations and will assemble the banished of Israel, and gather the dispersed of Judah from the four corners of the earth.' [A] Jeremiah 31:8 elaborates: 'Behold, I will bring them from the north country and gather them from the farthest parts of the earth, among them the blind and the lame, the pregnant woman and she who is in labor, together; a great company, they shall return here.'<br><br>[B] The theology here is covenantal: God's scattering of Israel (galah — exile) was punishment for covenant violation (Deut 28:64, 'The LORD will scatter you among all peoples, from one end of the earth to the other'). But the covenant also promised restoration upon repentance (Deut 30:3-4, 'The LORD your God will restore your fortunes and have mercy on you, and he will gather you again from all the peoples where the LORD your God has scattered you'). [B] 1 Enoch 57 presents this gathering as an eschatological certainty, not contingent on political maneuvering but enacted by angelic agents under divine decree.<br><br>[C] The historical context is critical. By the second century BC, the Jewish diaspora was vast: communities in Egypt (Alexandria), Babylon, Persia, Asia Minor, Greece, and Rome. The majority of Jews lived <em>outside</em> the land. [C] The question haunting these communities: Are we still God's people if we are not in the land? Texts like 1 Enoch 57, Tobit 13-14, and Psalms of Solomon 11 answer: Yes — the scattering is temporary and purposeful. God has not abandoned the covenant. The diaspora is not the end; the gathering is coming.<br><br>[B] This theology profoundly shaped early Christianity. Jesus is presented as the one who gathers the scattered (John 11:52, 'to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad'). Paul's mission to the Gentiles is framed as bringing in the 'fullness of the nations' before 'all Israel will be saved' (Rom 11:25-26). The church saw itself as participating in the eschatological ingathering prophesied in texts like 1 Enoch 57."
        },
        {
            "heading": "Purification of the Earth — Fire, Water, and Renewal (57:4-5)",
            "body": "[C] Enoch sees the earth undergoing purification: it is cleansed by both fire and water. This dual imagery is significant. [A] Water purification recalls the Flood (Gen 6-9), where the earth was 'washed' of violence and corruption. [A] Fire purification echoes prophetic texts like Malachi 3:2-3 ('He is like a refiner's fire... he will purify the sons of Levi') and Isaiah 66:15-16 ('For behold, the LORD will come in fire... by fire will the LORD enter into judgment').<br><br>[C] In Second Temple Judaism, the dual purification motif appears in multiple texts. The Community Rule from Qumran (1QS 4:20-21) speaks of God purging humanity 'by a spirit of holiness like purifying waters' and 'by a spirit of burning.' [C] 2 Peter 3:5-7 distinguishes the old world destroyed by water (the Flood) from the present world 'reserved for fire, being kept until the day of judgment.' [B] The pattern is: water judged the antediluvian world; fire will judge the present evil age; the age to come emerges from both purgations.<br><br>[B] The theological point: creation itself must be renewed before the righteous can inherit it. The earth is not merely real estate to be redistributed but a contaminated sanctuary requiring purification. [C] In Levitical law, purification by water and fire renders objects fit for holy use (Num 31:23, 'everything that can stand the fire, you shall pass through the fire, and it shall be clean'). [B] 1 Enoch 57 applies this cultic logic cosmically: the entire earth must pass through fire and water to become a fit dwelling place for the holy ones.<br><br>[B] This informs New Testament eschatology. Romans 8:19-22 speaks of creation itself 'groaning' in anticipation of liberation from bondage to decay. Revelation 21:1 declares, 'Then I saw a new heaven and a new earth, for the first heaven and the first earth had passed away.' The renewal is not <em>ex nihilo</em> (from nothing) but <em>ex vetere</em> (from the old) — the old creation purified and transformed, not annihilated and replaced."
        },
        {
            "heading": "The Removal of Oppressors — Justice for the Persecuted (57:5-6)",
            "body": "[C] A key element of the restoration vision is the removal of 'those who led astray' and 'those who oppressed.' This is not generic judgment but specific vindication of the persecuted faithful. [C] The historical referent is likely the Seleucid persecution under Antiochus IV Epiphanes (167-164 BC), when faithful Jews were forced to choose between apostasy and martyrdom (cf. 1 Macc 1:41-64, 2 Macc 6-7). [C] The 'oppressors' include both Gentile overlords and apostate Jews who collaborated with hellenization.<br><br>[A] The theme of God removing the wicked so the righteous can inherit is pervasive in the Psalms. Psalm 37:9-10: 'For the evildoers shall be cut off, but those who wait for the LORD shall inherit the land. In just a little while, the wicked will be no more; though you look carefully at his place, he will not be there.' [A] Proverbs 2:21-22: 'For the upright will inhabit the land, and those with integrity will remain in it, but the wicked will be cut off from the land, and the treacherous will be rooted out of it.'<br><br>[B] This is not arbitrary vengeance but covenant justice (mishpat). The wicked have violated the terms of habitation; they have made the land 'vomit them out' (Lev 18:25, 28). [B] The removal of oppressors is necessary for the land to be habitable for the righteous. You cannot have a holy community in an unholy environment ruled by the unrighteous. The cosmic order must be reset.<br><br>[C] This theology directly confronts the problem of theodicy: Why do the wicked prosper while the righteous suffer? The apocalyptic answer: The current order is temporary and unjust. God will intervene, remove the wicked, vindicate the righteous, and establish a just order. [C] This is the message of Daniel 7 (the beasts are judged, the saints receive the kingdom), Daniel 12 (the wicked will not understand, but the wise will shine like stars), and Wisdom of Solomon 3-5 (the righteous who seemed to die are actually at peace, while the wicked face sudden destruction).<br><br>[B] Jesus' parables participate in this tradition: the wheat and tares (Matt 13:24-30, 36-43), the dragnet (Matt 13:47-50), the sheep and goats (Matt 25:31-46). In each, there is a separation — the righteous are gathered, the wicked are removed. The kingdom cannot fully come until the rebels are expelled."
        },
        {
            "heading": "The Eschatological Inheritance — Land, Resurrection, and New Creation (57:6-7)",
            "body": "[C] The chapter concludes with the righteous inheriting their measured portions in a renewed earth. This is not a return to the status quo ante but an advance to a higher state. [B] The pattern is Edenic: humanity was placed in a garden-sanctuary to 'work and keep' it (Gen 2:15), lost access through sin (Gen 3:23-24), and now regains access in an eschatological restoration that surpasses the original.<br><br>[A] The land promise to Abraham (Gen 12:7, 15:18-21) was never fully realized in the Old Testament. Even at the height of the Davidic-Solomonic empire, Israel did not possess 'from the river of Egypt to the great river, the river Euphrates' (Gen 15:18). [B] Paul interprets this eschatologically in Romans 4:13: 'The promise to Abraham and his offspring that he would be heir of the world did not come through the law but through the righteousness of faith.' [B] The land promise expands to cosmic proportions — Abraham's seed will inherit not just Canaan but the renewed creation.<br><br>[C] The connection between land inheritance and resurrection is explicit in Jewish apocalyptic literature. Daniel 12:2-3: 'Many of those who sleep in the dust of the earth shall awake... And those who are wise shall shine like the brightness of the sky above.' [C] 4 Ezra 7:26-44 describes the eschatological land appearing after the resurrection: 'For indeed the time will come, when the signs that I have foretold to you will come to pass... and the land that now is hidden shall appear' (7:26-27). [C] 2 Baruch 29-30 links resurrection to the blossoming of the renewed earth: 'The earth will yield its fruit ten thousandfold... and those who are hungry will rejoice' (29:5-6).<br><br>[B] The logic: You cannot inherit land if you are dead. Therefore, restoration of the people to the land <em>requires</em> resurrection. This is why Ezekiel 37 uses resurrection imagery (dry bones coming to life) to describe national restoration. The metaphor works because the reality is literal: the eschatological ingathering will involve the resurrection of the righteous dead.<br><br>[B] This shapes the New Testament's already/not-yet tension. Jesus' resurrection is the 'firstfruits' (1 Cor 15:20, 23) — the beginning of the eschatological harvest. The kingdom has been inaugurated but not consummated. Believers are already 'sealed' and 'measured' (Eph 1:13-14, Rev 7:3-8), but the full inheritance awaits the resurrection and renewal of all things (Rom 8:23, 'we wait eagerly for adoption as sons, the redemption of our bodies'). [B] 1 Enoch 57's vision of angels measuring portions for the righteous is the blueprint for this eschatological program."
